passages.text: Wednesday, August 27, 2025

Retail net purchased \(\) 6.3B\(over the past week,\) \sim \$ 2B\(above the levels observed over the past month and in line with the weekly YTD average of\) \ \(6.5\) . Following a period of subdued activity, Friday marked a renewed surge of interest from retail investors, who resumed their daily purchases at \(\sim\) 1.4B/day, surpassing the daily average of \(\) 1.0\(B seen since May 1st. Notably, retail investors also became net buyers of single stocks (\) 1.3B this week) after remaining net sellers for an entire month, fueled by Tech. Retail traders have been notably contrarian investors this year, especially with NVDA: they aggressively bought the dip (\) 260Mn/day) during the sell- offs in Jan- Apr, then sold the rip ( \(\) 424Mn/day) in May, and more recently have been buying the stock at a reduced pace this quarter (\) 86Mn/day) (Figure 3). Following NVDA's earnings announcement, today's price action is proving another opportunity for retail to buy the NVDA dip, with a 12:30 cumulative imbalance at 4 times that of yesterday at the same time (Figure 12). Regarding NVDA options, retail investors are neutral on delta exposures but are short gamma, approaching levels seen prior to the tech sell- off in July last year (Figure 5). Looking beyond NVDA, retail investors have been engaging in AI stories at a slower pace in recent months compared to 1H25 (Figure 7 & Figure 8).

Retail investors continued to show a strong preference for ETFs \((+\) 5.0B) over Single Stocks \((+\) 1.3Mn). The majority of retail buying was concentrated in Large Caps ETFs \((+\) 1.4B, Figure 12), followed by Fixed Income Multi Sector \((+\) 315Mn) and Investment Grade \((+\) 215n). Call/put writing ETFs continued to attract flows at elevated levels this week \((+\) 163Mn, 4.2z). Meanwhile, retail sold Low Volatility \((+\) 58Mn), and Volatility ETFs \((+\) 56Mn). Individual ETF trends remained largely unchanged, with the largest inflows still in SPY \((+\) 392Mn, - 0.3z), QQQ \((+\) 371Mn, +0.3z), VOO \((+\) 184Mn, - 1.0z), TQQQ \((+\) 122Mn, +0.3z) and IVV \((+\) 77Mn, - 0.3z). The most sold ETFs this week were BIL \((+\) 82Mn, - 1.6z), USFR \((+\) 21Mn, - 1.1z), COWZ \((+\) 15Mn, - 0.8z), SHV \((+\) 13Mn, - 1.0z), and CONY \((+\) 11Mn, - 1.8z).

Within single stocks \((+\) 1.3B), retail investors bought into Cyclicals, Growth and AI/ Datacenter/ET/trification while they reversed course on IRA Green/EV/Climate Beneficiates (Figure 11). Among sectors, we saw inflows into Tech \((+\) 239Mn, 1.6z), Real Estate \((+\) 94Mn) and Utilities \((+\) 32Mn) and outflows from Cons. Disc. \((+\) 169Mn) and Energy \((+\) 151Mn). Retails continued to buy NVDA \((+\) 867Mn, 0.3z, of which \(\) 174Mn\(on the day of its earnings announcement on August 27th) as well as PLTR ( +\) 388Mn, 0.3z), OPEN \((+\) 97Mn, +3.8z), WMT \((+\) 89Mn, 2.0z) and CRVV \((+\) 89Mn, 0.6z). On the flipside, they continued to sell AAPL \((+\) 115Mn, 0.1z) and AVGO \((+\) 49Mn, - 0.7z), while changing gears on TSLA \((+\) 144Mn, - 0.3z), F \((+\) 77Mn, - 0.9z) and AMZN \((+\) 47Mn, - 1.0z).

Retail activity in options remained elevated with retail traders net selling \(\) 1.9B\(of delta and\) \ \(69B\) of gamma - yet another record. In the current risk- on rally, retail investors have been writing short- dated Index/ETF options at record levels (Figure 9). This poses a risk to their pnl in the event of a sudden vol shock, especially when VIX is near its YTD lows - implying the
risk reward may not be as favorable as it was couple of months ago.
- For the latest data, including intraday updates, visit Investable AI/Data Analytics.

- Non-retail investors sold \(1.3B last week, breaking their recent buying streak on Monday (vs YTD weekly avg of -\)9.2B and a 12m average of -\(9.1B). Meanwhile, futures traders continued their selling trend, with net sold over the week amounting to\)6.4B, driven by ES (\)2.8B), NQ (\)1.8B) and RTY (\)1.8B).

- Nvidia Corporation (NVDA, +\$867Mn last week, +0.3z): The stock was down as much as \(-5\%\) after market close following a slight miss on data center revenue, but has recovered to \(-1\%\) intra-day today. The rest of the report was better-than-expected, while the company did not provide any guidance related to its H20 shipments to China. However, our analysts estimate H20 potentially provides a \$2-5B (or more) upside revenue lever to 3Q, though this remains in question pending the resolution of "geopolitical issues," despite certain Chinese customers having already been granted export licenses by the US government, see analysts' review. Revenue guidance for next quarter stood at \$54B, above the consensus \$53.4B.- MongoDB (MDB, +\$3.7Mn last week, +0.5z): The database software provider reported jumped +38% after a strong earnings beat, attributed to growth on its cloud-based Atlas platform and a raise in its full-year guidance.- Kohls (KSS, - \$10Mn last week, -1.8z): The department store chain was +24% post earnings, which indicated successful cost-cutting measures and increased guidance for the rest of the year.- Canada Goose Holdings Inc (GOOS, - \$0.9Mn last week, -1.7z): The stock was +16% after the company's controlling shareholder was said to receive take-private bids, according to CNBC reports.
